[2] Honduras: request for information
Date: Fri 16 May 2014
Source: La Prensa [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.laprensa.hn/honduras/tegucigalpa/710038-98/confirman-que-ya-van-tres-casos-de-fiebre-chikungunya-en-honduras


Jose Antonio Samra, hospital pediatrician and clinical advisor to the national dengue program, stated that 3 cases of chikungunya fever were registered. [Transmission] is caused by the mosquitoes _Aedes aegypti_ and _Aedes albopictus_, and symptoms [of the virus infection] are similar to those of dengue.

The cases were confirmed in recent hours by specialists of the Hospital Escuela. The doctor explained that last year [2013], during an analysis of dengue cases, there were "3 people diagnosed [with chikungunya virus infection] by exclusion, that is to say that they were serologically tested and negative for dengue." Later, cross-reactive tests were done for chikungunya disease and 3 people resulted positive," the physician stated.

The specialist in dengue clinical management alerted the population to pay attention to symptoms such as fever, and joint pain and inflammation. Also, he indicated the necessity for the Secretariat of Health to initiate training of medical personnel to know more about the disease.

--
communicated by:
Roland Hubner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
Belgium
<roland.hubner@sante.belgique.be>

[This report does not provide enough information to present a convincing case for the occurrence of chikungunya virus infections in Honduras. The date in 2013 when the patients became ill was not given. The 1st known cases in the western hemisphere occurred in St Martin in December 2013. It is also not stated if the infections were acquired locally or elsewhere, and if local, specifically where. This is important information to have, and ProMED-mail would be interested in receiving it. The dengue test "by exclusion" simply indicates that these cases were not dengue virus infections. The details of the cross-reactive tests are not provided either. Establishment of a serological diagnosis of a chikungunya virus infection requires specific tests with that virus or its antigens. That may require sending the samples to a WHO reference laboratory for confirmation. In any event, there is no reported ongoing transmission.

Maps of Honduras can be accessed at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/honduras.jpg and
https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2482881,22. - Mod.TY]

