[9] Threat for Europe ex Caribbean
Date: August 2014
Source: Emerging Infectious Diseases journal [summ., edited]
http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/20/8/14-0650_article.htm#suggestedcitation


[ref: Mansuy JM, Grouteau E, Mengelle C, et al. Chikungunya in the Caribbean -- threat for Europe. Emerg Infect Dis [internet]. 2014; 20(8)]
------------------------------------------------------------------
In Southern France, 2 cases of chikungunya in siblings (an 8 year old girl and a 10 year old boy) were recently identified at the Toulouse University Hospital 2 days after these children had returned to France from the island of Martinique (French West Indies). These children developed acute fever associated with an arthromyalgic syndrome. The children had maculopapular, nonpruriginous rashes on their arms and legs, and endobuccal petechiae. The boy had bilateral knee effusions, and the girl had a measles-like rash that became more extended. Both children also had many mosquito bites that they scratched. They were discharged on the day of their admission. These 2 cases reported in metropolitan France after the patients visited Martinique indicate rapid spread of chikungunya virus.

_Ae. albopictus_ (Asian tiger mosquito) is also an efficient vector of chikungunya virus and is found in many areas, including southern Europe. This mosquito species was responsible for the extensive chikungunya outbreak on La Reunion Island in the Indian Ocean and was involved in the first chikungunya outbreak in Italy in 2007. _Ae. albopictus_ became established in a large area (91 150 sq km [35 193 sq mi]) of southern France in 2013, where approximately 13 million persons live.

The presence of an effective vector, its progressive spread, and the outbreak of chikungunya in the Western Hemisphere increase concerns of a chikungunya outbreak in Europe. The greatest challenge is to find a way of interrupting the transmission chain of the virus as soon as possible. This challenge requires an effective policy of informing travelers at risk, early screening based on rapid virologic diagnosis, and effective vector control. Such control measures need an educated population to ensure emptying standing water from flowerpots, gutters, buckets, pool covers, pet water dishes, and discarded tires. They also need global antivector measures (eradication of eggs, larvae, and adults of _Aedes_ spp. mosquitoes).

--
communicated by:
Roland Hubner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
Belgium
<roland.hubner@sante.belgique.be>

[_Ae. albopictus_ is present in many areas of the Mediterranean Basin, including southern France. The risk of viremic individuals who became infected with chikungunya virus in the Caribbean arriving in localities where this vector is present and initiating an outbreak in southern Europe is real.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Toulouse can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2482881,3934. - Mod.TY]
